1. Introduction¶

The project is dedicated to explore and analyse the Used car Prices dataset through unsupervised and supervised machine learning techniques. The selected dataset is second hand car prices for Barcelona province in 2022. It was retrieved from Kaggle and originally comes from zenodo.org. The dataset has 9 characteristics and 790 cars (observations).
The project consists of the following steps: data wrangling & exploratory data analysis, clustering and supervised learning. Every step is followed with the explanation of the procedure, analysis of results and their implications.

2. Data wrangling and EDA¶

The dataset contains 9 variables (exluding ID) related to the car advertised. There are 6 categorical variables - brand, model, engine, fuel, gearbox and location, and 3 continuous - price in euro, production year, mileage in km.

In [2]:
# Read data
db = pd.read_csv("https://github.com/mira7991/data_science_studio_assignment/raw/main/data/used_cars.csv.zip")

Data cleaning consist of (1) renaming of variables for future clean visualizations, (2) dropping variables of no interest, (3) dropping rows with NA values and (4) saving cleaned dataset. We drop engine (694 categories) and car model (206 categories) since they are more unique information and possibly would not be very useful for further analysis of clustering and prediction.

def histograms_plot(dataframe, columns, rows, cols):
    fig=plt.figure(figsize=(30, 40))
    for i, col in enumerate(columns):
        ax=fig.add_subplot(rows,cols,i+1)
        sns.histplot(dataframe, x=col)
        ax.set_title(col+" Distribution",color='red')
         
    # plt.show()

At first, before clustering, it is interesting to see the relationships between the different characteristics.The scatter plots below show relationships between different continuous variables. 3. Unsupervised learning¶

The goal of the clustering is to find groups with similar patterns. It can be used for further data analysis. For example, this can be useful for costumers and business to understand most common characteristics of the used cars in the clustered price range.

Building models¶

The three clustering models were built using K-means technique based on (1) raw values, (2) standardized values and (3) using Principal Component Analysis.

Visual analysis¶

Given that PCA values are simply linear combinations of the characteristics from the original data, it is clear from the plots of the cluster on the C1-C2 surface that the raw data and PCA values are clustered in the same way. On the other hand, standardised values are clustered quite differently, making it difficult to visually distinguish between 5 groups.

Quality check¶

Most common ways to assess the quality of clustering is using Calinski and Harabasz (C&H) score that shows the ratio of between over within dispersion. Raw values and PCA values clustering show significantly higher identical values compared to clustering of standardized values. It implies that former two are better models than the latter.

In [17]:

                                  k5_raw

chs_std = calinski_harabasz_score(db_2,

chs_pca = calinski_harabasz_score(db_2,

Optimizing number of clusters and choosing the model¶

The number of cluster in K-means can be optimized using C&H score. According to the line graph, the best K-means model with raw values has 10 clusters. Here, the choice of model depends on whether more complexity is desired. The difference is not big, so the K-means clustering with 5 clusters of raw values is the preferred model. Even though PCA reduces dimensions and complexity of the model, it is not easily interpretable, thus hard to tell the story. The choice always depends on the goal of the work, here, explore interesting patterns from the clustering.

Limitations¶

For the building clustering models only K-means technique was used. K-means model is good for numerical data as it calculates Euclidean distance. However, since the dataset contains both continuous and categorical data, it would've been more appropriate to use K-prototypes. This algorithm integrates k-modes and k-means and is able to group mixed continuous and categorical data.

3. Supervised learning¶

Linear regression model is type of supervised learning technique which can be used to predict continuous variable. It is based on the idea of reducing residual sum of squares between predicted and observed value. For this task, the price is be the predicted value while the rest of the variables are used to build the linear regression model. Since the Price is skewed (skew=1.2) variable we will use log of Price(skew=0.1).

Evaluation of the predictive performance¶

Predictive performance without cross validation. Three quality metrics were used to evaluate the performance with and without cross validation: Mean Absolute Error (MAE), Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) and R-squared. MAE shows the average of the absolute difference between the observed and predicted values. RMSE calculates the standard deviation of residuals. R-squared shows the proportion of the variability that can be explained by the model. Since former two gives results in the same unit as the variable, it is better to see them in real price than log price. Therefore, the Price variable and converted predicted values are used for the evaluation.

The model produces results of quite low quality. It can only explain 15% of the variation in price prediction. MAE and RMSE both quantify the average difference in errors, where the first is linear and the second is quadratic. As a result, the latter penalises significant errors more severely. These metrics indicate high model errors, 3925 and 5519 Euro, respectively.

To build the model with cross-validation, we need to split the dataset into train and test subsets and make the model learn on train subset.

In [106]:
# Building model with Cross-validation

# Train/test split
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,
                                                    log_price,
                                                    test_size=0.8
                                                   )

# Linear regression
lm_estimator = LinearRegression()
# Fit on X/Y train|
lm_estimator.fit(x_train, y_train)
# Predict on X test
test_y_pred = lm_estimator.predict(x_test)

                                                            np.expm1(test_y_pred)),
                         'RMSE': sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(np.expm1(y_test),

The model with cross-validation shows better results than without. It shows that 49% of variablity in prediction of the price can be explained by the model and gives lower error metrics. The fact that it shows better performance may happen due to random splitting of training and testing subsets. It is recommended to use K-fold CV to get the mean of different random splittings that will ensure that we used all data(both from test and train) to evaluate the model.

Using K-fold shows even better results - mean R-squared for 5 folds(groups) is 62.5%. Seems like the model after all is not that bad for prediction of the price for the used car.

In [128]:
# K-fold CV
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

lm_kcv_r2 = cross_val_score(LinearRegression(),
                              X,
                              log_price,
                              cv=5,
                              scoring="r2"
                             )

lm_kcv_r2.mean()

Conclusion¶

Throughout the project, the analysis of used automobiles revealed some interesting patterns in the Barcelona market, such as the majority of cars having manual engines, diesel being the most prevalent fuel type, and average value of roughly 150000 EUR. Furthermore, it was intriguing to investigate the relationship between pricing and automotive characteristics. Five groups with similar patterns were identified using K-means clustering, which can be utilised to better understand characteristics as a group for customers or second automobile resale business. Linear regression was used to forecast the price of the car based on its attributes, and K-fold validation revealed that the model has relatively good performance (mean R2=62.5%) and can be improved further by removing or adding other features.
